---
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import "../../../styles/global.css";

const breadcrumbSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
  "itemListElement": [
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Guides", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/guides/" },
    { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 3, "name": "Student Loan Repayment in NZ", "item": "https://takehomepay.nz/guides/student-loan-repayment-nz/" }
  ]
};

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Are NZ student loans really interest-free?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, student loans are interest-free for borrowers who are New Zealand-based, meaning you live in New Zealand for at least 183 days in each tax year. If you move overseas and are no longer NZ-based, interest is charged on your remaining loan balance at a rate set by the government. Staying in New Zealand keeps your loan interest-free, which is a significant benefit compared to student loan systems in many other countries."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I make voluntary repayments to pay off my student loan faster?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, you can make voluntary repayments at any time on top of the compulsory deductions from your wages. You can make extra payments directly to IRD via internet banking, credit card, or at a Westpac branch. Since the loan is interest-free for NZ-based borrowers, some people prefer to invest their money elsewhere rather than making extra repayments, but paying off the loan sooner reduces your long-term deductions and increases your take home pay."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What happens to my student loan if I go overseas?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If you leave New Zealand for more than 183 days in a tax year, your student loan becomes overseas-based and interest begins accruing. You are also required to make repayments based on your loan balance regardless of your income. You must inform IRD before you leave and set up an overseas repayment arrangement. Penalties apply for non-compliance, and overdue amounts attract additional interest. Many borrowers choose to repay their loan before leaving to avoid accumulating interest."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="Student Loan Repayment in NZ: Thresholds & How Much You Pay | TakeHomePay.nz"
  description="How student loan repayments work in New Zealand. Learn about the 12% repayment rate, the $22,828 threshold, interest-free rules, and what happens when you go overseas."
  canonical="/guides/student-loan-repayment-nz/"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(breadcrumbSchema)} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />

  <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-primary to-primary-light py-12">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 text-center text-white">
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl font-bold mb-4 text-white">Student Loan Repayment in NZ: Thresholds & How Much You Pay</h1>
      <p class="text-lg text-white/90">A complete guide to understanding and managing your New Zealand student loan repayments.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="py-12 sm:py-16">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="mb-8 text-sm text-text-muted">
        <ol class="flex items-center gap-2 flex-wrap">
          <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Home</a></li>
          <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mx-2 before:text-border"><a href="/guides/" class="hover:text-primary transition-colors">Guides</a></li>
          <li class="before:content-['/'] before:mx-2 before:text-border font-medium text-text">Student Loan Repayment</li>
        </ol>
      </nav>

      <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <p>
          New Zealand's student loan scheme makes tertiary education accessible to thousands of New Zealanders every year. Managed by StudyLink (a service of the Ministry of Social Development) for borrowing and Inland Revenue (IRD) for repayment, the scheme provides loans for tuition fees, course-related costs, and living expenses to eligible students. Once you finish studying and enter the workforce, repaying your student loan becomes an automatic part of your pay cycle, deducted alongside PAYE tax and other employment deductions.
        </p>

        <p>
          This guide explains how student loan repayments work for the 2025-2026 tax year, including the current repayment threshold, the deduction rate, how repayments are calculated on different income types, and what happens if you move overseas. Whether you are about to graduate, have just started your first job with a student loan, or have been repaying for years and want to understand the numbers better, this guide covers everything you need to know.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">How Repayments Work</h2>

        <p>
          Student loan repayments in New Zealand are collected through the PAYE system, meaning your employer deducts them from your pay automatically, just like income tax. You do not need to set up separate payments or remember due dates. As long as your employer has the correct tax code, the right amount will be deducted from each pay packet.
        </p>

        <p>
          For the 2025-2026 tax year, the repayment rate is 12 percent on every dollar of income you earn above the annual repayment threshold of $22,828. This threshold equates to approximately $439 per week or $878 per fortnight. If you earn less than the threshold, no repayments are deducted. If you earn above it, only the income above the threshold attracts the 12 percent deduction.
        </p>

        <p>
          For example, if you earn $60,000 per year, your income above the threshold is $60,000 minus $22,828 equals $37,172. Your annual repayment is 12 percent of $37,172, which is $4,460.64. Spread over 26 fortnightly pay periods, that works out to approximately $171.56 per fortnight.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">The Repayment Threshold</h2>

        <p>
          The repayment threshold is the income level below which no student loan repayments are required. For the 2025-2026 tax year, this annual threshold is $22,828. The threshold is reviewed periodically and may be adjusted by the government. It is designed to protect low-income borrowers from having to make repayments when their earnings are modest.
        </p>

        <p>
          It is important to note that the threshold applies to your total income from all sources, not just your primary employment. If you have a second job, investment income, or self-employment income, these are all included when determining your total income for student loan repayment purposes. However, the compulsory deductions from your wages are based on the earnings from each specific job. At the end of the tax year, IRD reconciles your total income and may require additional repayments or issue a refund if too much was deducted.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Tax Codes for Student Loan Borrowers</h2>

        <p>
          If you have a student loan, you must use a tax code that includes the letters "SL" so that your employer knows to deduct student loan repayments. The most common tax codes for borrowers are MSL (primary employment with student loan), MESL (primary employment with student loan and IETC entitlement), and the secondary income codes SSL, SHSL, or STSL.
        </p>

        <p>
          Using the wrong tax code can cause problems. If you use the "M" code instead of "MSL", no student loan repayments will be deducted during the year, and you will face a lump-sum bill from IRD after your end-of-year assessment. Conversely, if you mistakenly use a student loan tax code when your loan is already paid off, repayments will be deducted unnecessarily. While IRD will refund over-deductions, it is much simpler to have the right code from the start.
        </p>

        <p>
          You can check your student loan balance and whether you still have an active loan through your myIR account on the IRD website. If your loan is close to being paid off, IRD will notify your employer to stop deductions once the balance reaches zero.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Interest-Free Student Loans</h2>

        <p>
          One of the most significant features of the New Zealand student loan scheme is that loans are interest-free for borrowers who remain New Zealand-based. This means that as long as you live in New Zealand for at least 183 days in each tax year, no interest is charged on your student loan balance. Your repayments go entirely towards reducing your principal balance, and the amount you repay over time equals the amount you originally borrowed minus any repayments already made.
        </p>

        <p>
          This interest-free policy, introduced in 2006, is a major financial benefit for New Zealand graduates. In many other countries, student loan interest adds significantly to the total amount borrowers repay. For example, in the United Kingdom, student loans accrue interest linked to inflation plus a margin, and in the United States, federal student loan interest rates can range from 4 to 7 percent. The New Zealand system means that there is no financial penalty for taking longer to repay your loan, as the balance does not grow over time while you remain in the country.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Repayments for Self-Employed Borrowers</h2>

        <p>
          If you are self-employed or earn income that does not have PAYE deducted at source, your student loan repayments are calculated and paid as part of your income tax return. You include your student loan repayment obligation in your IR3 individual tax return at the end of each tax year. IRD calculates the amount owed based on your net income above the repayment threshold, and you may be required to make interim payments during the year based on your prior year's income.
        </p>

        <p>
          For borrowers who have a mix of PAYE employment and self-employment income, the situation requires careful management. PAYE deductions cover the employment income, while the self-employment income is addressed through the tax return process. Getting professional tax advice is recommended for self-employed borrowers to ensure compliance and avoid unexpected bills.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">What Happens When You Go Overseas</h2>

        <p>
          Moving overseas has significant implications for your student loan. If you are absent from New Zealand for more than 183 days in a tax year, you become "overseas-based" and your loan is no longer interest-free. Interest accrues on your balance at a rate set annually by the government, which has historically ranged from around 2 to 4 percent.
        </p>

        <p>
          In addition to interest, you are required to make repayments based on your loan balance rather than your income. IRD sets repayment obligations for overseas-based borrowers using a schedule tied to the outstanding balance. These repayments can be substantial, especially for large loan balances. You must contact IRD before you leave New Zealand to set up an overseas repayment arrangement. Failure to meet your repayment obligations while overseas results in penalties and additional interest charges, which can cause the loan balance to grow significantly.
        </p>

        <p>
          If you are planning a temporary trip overseas, such as a holiday or short-term work assignment, you can apply for a temporary repayment exemption to avoid being reclassified as overseas-based. This exemption is available for absences of up to certain lengths depending on the circumstances. If you are going overseas for an extended period, carefully consider whether it is worth paying off your loan before you leave to avoid interest charges.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Voluntary Repayments</h2>

        <p>
          You can make voluntary repayments at any time to pay off your student loan faster. Extra payments can be made through internet banking, direct debit, at a Westpac branch, or through your myIR account. There is no minimum or maximum for voluntary payments, and no penalty for early repayment.
        </p>

        <p>
          Whether you should make voluntary repayments is a personal financial decision. Since the loan is interest-free for NZ-based borrowers, some people prefer to invest their spare money elsewhere, where it may earn a return. Others prefer the certainty and peace of mind of eliminating their loan as quickly as possible. The "right" choice depends on your individual financial goals, risk tolerance, and priorities. However, it is generally advisable to prioritise higher-interest debt (such as credit cards or personal loans) before making voluntary student loan repayments.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Repayment Examples</h2>

        <p>
          To illustrate how student loan repayments work at different income levels, here are some examples for the 2025-2026 tax year, all based on the $22,828 annual threshold and 12 percent repayment rate:
        </p>

        <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
          <table class="w-full border-collapse border border-border text-sm">
            <thead>
              <tr class="bg-surface-alt">
                <th class="border border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-bold text-primary">Annual Income</th>
                <th class="border border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-bold text-primary">Income Above Threshold</th>
                <th class="border border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-bold text-primary">Annual Repayment</th>
                <th class="border border-border px-4 py-3 text-left font-bold text-primary">Fortnightly Deduction</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$30,000</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$7,172</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$860.64</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$33.10</td></tr>
              <tr class="bg-surface"><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$50,000</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$27,172</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$3,260.64</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$125.41</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$70,000</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$47,172</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$5,660.64</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$217.72</td></tr>
              <tr class="bg-surface"><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$100,000</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$77,172</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$9,260.64</td><td class="border border-border px-4 py-3">$356.18</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p>
          These figures show that higher earners repay their loans more quickly because a larger proportion of their income exceeds the threshold. Someone earning $100,000 repays more than ten times the amount of someone earning $30,000 per year.
        </p>

        <!-- FAQ Section -->
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-primary mt-10 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="space-y-4 not-prose">
          <details class="border border-border rounded-xl p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-bold text-primary cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
              Are NZ student loans really interest-free?
              <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-text leading-relaxed">Yes, student loans are interest-free for borrowers who are New Zealand-based, meaning you live in New Zealand for at least 183 days in each tax year. If you move overseas and are no longer NZ-based, interest is charged on your remaining loan balance at a rate set by the government. Staying in New Zealand keeps your loan interest-free, which is a significant benefit compared to student loan systems in many other countries.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-border rounded-xl p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-bold text-primary cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
              Can I make voluntary repayments to pay off my student loan faster?
              <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-text leading-relaxed">Yes, you can make voluntary repayments at any time on top of the compulsory deductions from your wages. You can make extra payments directly to IRD via internet banking, credit card, or at a Westpac branch. Since the loan is interest-free for NZ-based borrowers, some people prefer to invest their money elsewhere rather than making extra repayments, but paying off the loan sooner reduces your long-term deductions and increases your take home pay.</p>
          </details>

          <details class="border border-border rounded-xl p-4 group">
            <summary class="font-bold text-primary cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between">
              What happens to my student loan if I go overseas?
              <span class="text-accent transition-transform group-open:rotate-45 text-xl">+</span>
            </summary>
            <p class="mt-3 text-text leading-relaxed">If you leave New Zealand for more than 183 days in a tax year, your student loan becomes overseas-based and interest begins accruing. You are also required to make repayments based on your loan balance regardless of your income. You must inform IRD before you leave and set up an overseas repayment arrangement. Penalties apply for non-compliance, and overdue amounts attract additional interest. Many borrowers choose to repay their loan before leaving to avoid accumulating interest.</p>
          </details>
        </div>

        <!-- Related Tools -->
        <div class="mt-10 border border-border rounded-xl p-6 bg-surface">
          <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-primary mb-3">Related Tools & Guides</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
            <li><a href="/" class="text-accent hover:underline">NZ Salary Calculator</a> - See how student loan repayments affect your take home pay</li>
            <li><a href="/guides/paye-tax-nz/" class="text-accent hover:underline">PAYE Tax in New Zealand</a> - Understanding the tax system that collects your repayments</li>
            <li><a href="/guides/tax-codes-nz/" class="text-accent hover:underline">NZ Tax Codes Explained</a> - Make sure you have the right SL tax code</li>
            <li><a href="/guides/first-job-new-zealand/" class="text-accent hover:underline">Starting Your First Job in NZ</a> - Setting up student loan deductions correctly from day one</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Sources -->
        <div class="mt-8 border-t border-border pt-6">
          <h2 class="text-lg font-bold text-primary mb-3">Sources</h2>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-sm text-text-muted">
            <li><a href="https://www.ird.govt.nz/student-loans" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:underline">IRD - Student loans</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.ird.govt.nz/student-loans/repaying-my-student-loan" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:underline">IRD - Repaying your student loan</a></li>
            <li><a href="https://www.employment.govt.nz/hours-and-wages/pay/taxes-and-deductions/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:underline">Employment New Zealand - Taxes and deductions</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
